# Domain vs Voice and External Boundary

The internal domain (user, session, exercise, set, set group) and the voice-pipeline / external APIs must remain separate.

This boundary is one of the most important architectural protections in the repository.

## Core Rule

Internal business entities must not be shaped around voice-API output format, OAuth provider payloads, or transport concerns.

Voice-API and OAuth outputs should be mapped into the internal domain through dedicated parsing and auth layers.

## Internal Domain Should Model

The domain layer should model concepts such as:

- user
- session (start/end time, duration, state)
- exercise (name or identifier)
- set (exercise, weight, reps, notes, order)
- set group (superset/triset, sets, notes)
- lifecycle semantics (pending, confirmed, persisted)

These are business and workflow concepts.

## Voice Pipeline and External Layer Should Handle

The voice pipeline and external integrations should handle:

- voice-to-text API calls and response shape
- raw text → parsed structure (ParseExerciseSkill, GroupSeriesSkill)
- validation and error categories (unrecognized, incomplete, conflict)
- OAuth login flow and token refresh
- mapping external identity to internal user

These are integration and pipeline concerns.

## Do Not

Do not:

- introduce voice-API–specific field names or structures directly into core domain entities
- make the domain layer depend on voice-to-text clients or OAuth SDKs
- put parsing or grouping logic inside domain services (keep it in the voice pipeline)
- leak transport or serialization concerns into business rules
- use framework or request objects in the domain layer

## Acceptable Pattern

The preferred pattern is:

voice API text → voice pipeline (parse, group, validate) → structured set(s) or error category → application layer → domain model → persistence

OAuth provider → auth layer → internal user/session → domain and API

## Review Trigger

If a change introduces voice-API– or OAuth-specific semantics directly into:

- domain entities
- domain services
- generic validation code that should be pipeline-agnostic
- unrelated API handlers

treat it as a structural problem and stop.

## Final Rule

Protect the internal domain from voice-API and external-integration complexity. That separation keeps the system easier to evolve, test, and reason about.
